<chapter xml:id="chapter-inf-behaviour" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Long-term and singular behaviour</title>

<section xml:id="section-inf-behaviour-horiz">
<title>Long-term behaviour</title>

<introduction><p>
	As we will explore further in subsequent chapters,
	we often create mathematical functions to model physical systems and patterns.
	We use models to predict the behaviour of a system,
	and one of the most natural questions to try to answer using a model is
	<q>What will happen a long time from now?</q>
	For some models,
	the answer might be that the system's output approaches some <q>steady state</q> value.
	For other models,
	the answer might be that the system's output grows without bound.
	In this section,
	we develop a process for detecting these patterns.
</p></introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Definition and first examples</title>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-horiz">
	<title>Long-term behaviour</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>f(t)</m> is a function whose domain contains an infinite subdomain <m>t \gt t_0</m>.
		<ol>

			<li>
				<title>Unbounded growth</title>
				<p>
				We write <md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
				to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> eventually become and stay positive and arbitrarily large in magnitude.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Unbounded decay</title>
				<p>
				We write <md> f(t) \to - \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
				to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> eventually become and stay negative and arbitrarily large in magnitude.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Approaching steady-state</title>
				<p>
				For some steady-state output value <m>L</m>,
				we write <md> f(t) \to L \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
				to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> eventually become and stay arbitrarily close to <m>L</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

		</ol>
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<warning>
	<title>Infinity is not a number</title>
	<p>
	There is a reason we write <m>f(t) \to \infty</m> instead of <m>f(t) = \infty</m>.
	Infinity is not a number,
	so it is not permitted as an output of a function.
	Instead, we use the <q>idea</q> of infinity to indicate unbounded behaviour.
	</p>
	<aside valign="middle"><title>Further investigation</title><p>
		It is possible to create mathematical systems where infinity <em>can</em> be considered a number,
		but such discussion is beyond the scope of this course.
	</p></aside>
</warning>

<p>
There are words and phrases in <xref ref="definition-inf-behaviour-horiz" /> that have special, technical meanings in mathematics,
and it's important to understand their technical meanings in order to be able to properly verify these definitions in more complex examples.
</p>

<p>
For the case of <m>f(t) \to \infty</m>,
<term>arbitrarily large</term> means the function's output values are able to grow larger than <em>every</em> proposed upper limit level,
no matter how large,
<em>and stay above that level</em> forever more.
In this case,
<term>eventually</term> means that for a particular proposed upper limit level,
we may have to go very far out into the domain to achieve outputs that grow and stay larger than the proposed limit,
and how far out we need to go to observe this behaviour will vary depending on the size of the proposed upper limit level that we need to beat.
For the case of <m>f(t) \to -\infty</m>,
we want to demonstrate that the function's output values will eventually fall <em>below</em> every proposed <em>lower</em> limit level,
and stay below that level forever more.
</p>

<p>
<term>Arbitrarily close</term> has a similar meaning as in the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-point-continuous" text="title"/></term>
<mdash />
it means that we are always able to restrict the function's output values to within a small range around <m>L</m>,
no matter how small,
so that the function's output values move and then stay within that small range forever more.
Here,
<term>eventually</term> has a similar meaning as before,
where we may need to go very far out into the domain to achieve outputs that move and stay within the proposed restricted range,
and how far out we need to go to observe this behaviour will vary depending on the size of the range.
</p>

<warning><p>
	You should not take <md> f(t) \to L \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
	to mean <q>eventually <m>f(t) = L</m>,</q>
	nor should you take it to mean <q><m>f(t)</m> becomes close to <m>L</m> but never actually equals <m>L</m>.</q>
	Either situation <em>could</em> happen (though obviously not both simultaneously for a particular function),
	but neither <em>needs</em> to happen.
	For example,
	<!-- in a later chapter -->
	in <xref ref="chapter-periodic" />
	we will see examples of functions that oscillate between values above and below a certain level <m>L</m>,
	crossing that level as it moves from one to the other,
	while still <q>narrowing down</q> to becoming closer and closer to <m>L</m>.
</p></warning>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-parabola">
	<title>Unbounded growth of the square function</title>

	<p>
	For function <m>f(t) = t^2</m>,
	we have <m>f(t) \to \infty</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	By this we mean that no upper bound can be put on the growth of this function.
	For example the output values eventually get above <m>100</m>,
	as they stay above that level for all <m>t \gt 10</m>.
	And the output values also eventually get above <m>100</m> trillion,
	as they stay above that level for all <m>t \gt {10}^7</m>.
	And if <m>M</m> represents the largest number you can think of plus one,
	then the output values also grow above that level,
	staying above it for all <m>t \gt \sqrt{M}</m>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-parabola">
		<caption> The function <m>f(t) = t^2</m> grows beyond any potential ceiling. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-unbdd-growth-parabola" width="40.2%">
			<shortdescription> Graph demonstrating that a parabola grows beyond any potential ceiling. </shortdescription>
			<description><p>
				The graph of the function <m>f(t) = t^2</m> is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes over the domain <m>t \ge 0</m>.
				This graph takes the shape of one-half of a parabola with vertex at the origin.
				A potential upper bound for the function is marked approximately two-thirds of the way up the vertical axis,
				labelled as <m>M</m>,
				and the horizontal line <m>q = M</m> is drawn as a dashed line.
				This line necessarily intersects the graph,
				and a dashed vertical line is drawn from the point of intersection down to the horizontal axis.
				The position where this vertical line meets the horizontal axis is labelled as <m>\sqrt{M}</m>.
				Finally,
				the portion of the graph that lies above the level <m>q = M</m>
				(and, for this graph, therefore also to the right of the position <m>t = \sqrt{M}</m>),
				is drawn in red to highlight the fact that it is evidence that <m>q = M</m> is <em>not</em> an upper bound for the graph.
			</p></description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/unbdd-growth-parabola.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-steady-state-one-over-sq">
	<title>Approaching steady-state</title>

	<p>
	Consider function <md> f(t) = 2 + \frac{1}{t^2} </md>.
	Large values of <m>t</m> make the fraction part of the formula very small,
	and the larger <m>t</m> gets,
	the smaller that fraction gets.
	So we might guess that <md> f(t) \to 2 \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty</md>.
	</p>

	<p>
	To verify this,
	we should consider different ranges around that proposed <q>steady-state</q> output level.
	<ul>

		<li>
			Do values of <m>f(t)</m> eventually move and stay within the range <m>1 \lt f(t) \lt 3</m>?
			Yes, they will do so for all <m>t \gt 1</m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			Do values of <m>f(t)</m> eventually move and stay within the range <m>1.99 \lt f(t) \lt 2.01</m>?
			Yes, they will do so for all <m>t \gt 10</m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			Do values of <m>f(t)</m> eventually move and stay within the range of <m>2</m> plus or minus one one-hundred-trillionth?
			Yes, they will do so for all <m>t \gt {10}^7</m>.
		</li>

	</ul>
	Ultimately, you can ask the above question with any small range
	<md> 2 - \epsilon \lt f(t) \lt 2 + \epsilon </md>
	you like
	(where <m>\epsilon</m> represents a very small amount above or below <m>2</m>)
	and the answer will always be
	<q>Yes, for all <m>t \gt 1/\sqrt{\epsilon}</m>.</q>
	This verifies that output values of <m>f(t)</m> become arbitrarily close to <m>2</m> in the long-term.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-error-bounds">
		<caption> The function <m>f(t) = 2 + 1/t^2</m> eventually moves within every arbitrarily small range around a proposed approximate long-term value. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-error-bounds" width="47.9%">
			<shortdescription>
				Graph demonstrating that a shifted reciprocal power function eventually moves within every arbitrarily small range around a proposed approximate long-term value.
			</shortdescription>
			<description><p>
				The portion of the graph of the function <m>f(t) = 2 + 1 / t^2</m> that lies in the first quadrant is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
				The horizontal line <m>q = 2</m> is drawn as a dashed line,
				to be considered as a potential horizontal asymptote for the graph.
				To this end,
				the horizontal lines <m>q = 2 + \epsilon</m> and <m>q = 2 - \epsilon</m> are drawn symmetrically above and below and close to the line <m>q = 2</m>
				(also as dashed lines),
				where <m>\epsilon</m> represents an unspecified small value.
				The line <m>q = 2 + \epsilon</m> intersects the graph,
				and a dashed vertical line is drawn from the point of intersection down to the horizontal axis.
				The position where this vertical line meets the horizontal axis is labelled as <m>1 / \sqrt{\epsilon}</m>.
				The portion of the graph to the right of this position
				(that is, on domain <m>t \gt 1 / \sqrt{\epsilon}</m>)
				is drawn in red to highlight that it remains within the range
				<m>2 - \epsilon \lt q \lt 2 + \epsilon</m>.
			</p></description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/error-bounds.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
When steady-state long-term behaviour <m>f(t) \to L</m> occurs,
as in <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-steady-state-one-over-sq" />,
we often place a dashed horizontal line at that level when drawing the function's graph.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-hasymp">
	<title>Horizontal asymptote</title>
	<statement><p>
		A horizontal line that a function's graph approaches,
		becoming closer and closer to it as one goes further out on the graph.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-horiz-asymp">
	<caption> The graph of <m>f(t) = 2 + 1 / t^2</m> approaches a horizontal asymptote at height <m>2</m>. </caption>
	<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-horiz-asymp" width="45.5%">
		<shortdescription> A function's graph approaching a horizontal asymptote. </shortdescription>
		<description><p>
			The graph of the function <m>f(t) = 2 + 1 / t^2</m> is drawn as approaching the horizontal asymptote <m>q = 2</m> from above on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
			The horizontal asymptote <m>q = 2</m> is drawn as a dashed line.
		</p></description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/horiz-asymp.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Finally, here is an example where the long-term behaviour does not fall into any of the categories in
<xref ref="definition-inf-behaviour-horiz" />.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Modelling pulsar emissions</title>

	<p>
	A <term>pulsar</term> is a type of star that only emits electromagnetic radiation from its magnetic poles.
	As a pulsar rotates,
	its emissions become visible to anyone in the path of its beam for a split second before the beam rotates away from the observer again.
	Essentially, a pulsar is an enormous strobe light in space.
	If we create a simple model function <m>R(t)</m> of the radiation received by an observer,
	we might come up with something like the graph in <xref ref="figure-inf-behaviour-pulsar" />
	with there are repeating, short <q>on</q> and <q>off</q> periods,
	with a constant emission level of <m>R_0</m> during the <q>on</q> periods.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-pulsar">
		<caption> A model of the observed on/off pattern of a pulsar. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-pulsar" width="88.8%">
			<shortdescription> A graphical model of the observed on/off pattern of a pulsar. </shortdescription>
			<description><p>
				The graph of a piecewise function is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
				Each piece of the graph is a horizontal line.
				On domain <m>t \ge 0</m>,
				the graph begins at a closed endpoint on and near the top of the vertical axis,
				at a level labelled <m>R_0</m>.
				From this closed endpoint a horizontal line segment extends a short distance into the first quadrant and ends at an open endpoint.
				The graph continues with a closed endpoint on the horizontal axis directly below the open endpoint where the first line segment ended.
				From this closed endpoint a horizontal line segment extends a short distance along the horizontal axis (twice the length of the first segment) and ends at an open endpoint.
				From there the graph repeats,
				alternating shorter horizontal segments at level <m>q = R_0</m> and slightly longer horizontal segments along the horizontal axis.
				Also,
				a short segment is drawn along the horizontal axis to the left of the vertical axis,
				ending in an open endpoint at the origin,
				to indicate that this repeating pattern also extends into the domain <m>t \lt 0</m>.
			</p></description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/pulsar.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	It would not be appropriate to write either <m>R(t) \to \pm \infty</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
	as clearly the functions values are neither growing nor decaying,
	only flip-flopping.
	And it would also not be appropriate to write either <m>R(t) \to R_0</m> or <m>R(t) \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
	for the following reason.
	If we consider the range
	<md> \frac{R_0}{2} \lt R(t) \lt \frac{3 R_0}{2} </md>
	which contains <m>R_0</m>,
	then the function's output values will not move and <em>stay</em> within that range since after a very short time of moving within that bound it will once again flop out of the bound.
	And a similar argument can be made about the range
	<md> -\frac{R_0}{2} \lt R(t) \lt \frac{R_0}{2} </md>
	containing <m>0</m>.
	No matter how far out on the timeline we go,
	we always see this same behaviour of not staying within a small range around any one particular output level.
	</p>

	<p>
	In reality,
	a pulsar loses energy over tens of millions of years,
	slowing down and eventually <q>turning off.</q>
	So the fact that our mathematical analysis above is at odds with our expectations from knowledge of physics is a good indication that our simple model is only appropriate for short-term analysis,
	and a more sophisticated model should be used for long-term analysis.
	</p>

</example>


</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-inf-behaviour-patterns">
<title>Fundamental long-term behaviour patterns</title>

<p>
Here are some simple but fundamental patterns that we will use to analyze more complex examples,
by recognizing these patterns as <q>pieces</q> of the more complex ones.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-inf-behaviour-constant">
	<title>Long-term behaviour of constants</title>
	<p>
	A constant function <m>f(t) = c</m> always satisfies <m>f(t) \to c</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
	since a function that stays at the single output level <m>c</m> will always stay within every possible small range containing <m>c</m>.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-inf-behaviour-lines">
	<title>Long-term behaviour of lines</title>
	<p>
	For linear function <m>q(t) = m t + q_0</m>,
	we have
	<md> q(t) \to \pm \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>,
	where the <em>plus-or-minus</em> depends on whether the constant rate factor <m>m</m> is positive or negative.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-inf-behaviour-powers">
	<title>Long-term behaviour of powers</title>
	<p>
	For power function <m>p(t) = t^m</m> with a positive exponent <m>m</m>,
	we have
	<md> p(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-powers">
	<title>Long-term behaviour of reciprocal powers</title>
	<p>
	For every positive exponent <m>m</m>,
	the function <md> f(t) = \frac{1}{t^m} </md> will exhibit long-term behaviour
	<md> f(t) \to 0 \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>.
	</p>
</identity>

<p> We can turn <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-powers" /> into a more general pattern. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-of-inf">
	<title>Long-term behaviour of reciprocals</title>
	<p>
	If <m>f(t)</m> is a function for which we know that
	<md> f(t) \to \pm \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
	(where the <em>plus-or-minus</em> means that we know that one or the other is true),
	then the reciprocal function <md> g(t) = \frac{1}{f(t)} </md>
	will satisfy
	<md> g(t) \to 0 \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>.
	</p>
</identity>

<warning>
	<title>Converse of <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-of-inf" /></title>
	<p>
	We have to be careful with attempting to reverse <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-of-inf" />.
	If we have a function <m>f(t)</m> for which we know that
	<md> f(t) \to 0 \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>,
	it <em>may</em> be the case that the reciprocal function <md> g(t) = \frac{1}{f(t)}</md> satisfies one of
	<md> g(t) \to \pm \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>,
	but it may not.
	For example, it could be that <m>f(t) \to 0</m> occurs by oscillating between positive and negative values but with ever-decreasing <q>peaks,</q>
	making the reciprocal function <m>g(t)</m> oscillate between large positive and large negative output values.
	Even worse,
	the function <m>f(t)</m> may cross the <m>0</m> level an infinite number of times as it oscillates,
	making the output value of the reciprocal function <m>g(t)</m> undefined at all of those input values.
	</p>
</warning>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Analyzing more complex examples</title>

<p>
In general,
we analyze more complex examples by breaking them into pieces.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Combination of different behaviours</title>
	<p>
	Consider function <md> f(t) = 2 + \frac{1}{t^2} - t^2 </md>.
	Individually,
	we know that
	<md>
		<mrow>
			2 \amp \to 2 \amp
			\frac{1}{t^2} \amp \to 0 \amp
			t^2 \to \infty
		</mrow>
	</md>
	as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	So overall,
	the outputs of <m>f(t)</m> will get large in the long-term.
	However, noticing the minus sign in front of the <m>t^2</m> term in the formula for <m>f(t)</m>,
	we conclude
	<md> f(t) \to -\infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-rational-infinities">
	<title>A rational expression of <q>infinities</q></title>

	<p>
	Consider rational function <md> f(t) = \frac{2 t^4 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </md>.
	Based on <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-powers" />,
	every nonconstant term in both numerator and denominator approaches one of <m>\pm \infty</m>.
	Will the two <q>infinities</q> in the denominator <q>cancel</q> each other because of the minus sign between them?
	Will the <q>infinities</q> in the numerator and denominator <q>cancel</q> each other,
	resulting in a ratio approaching <m>1</m>?
	</p>

	<p>
	Obtaining the answers to both questions requires considering the relative sizes involved.
	We are not literally adding, subtracting, and dividing infinities in this expression <mdash />
	we are looking for a pattern in the actual output values for large <em>but finite</em> values of <m>t</m>.
	And for large powers of <m>t</m>, <em>the larger the exponent, the larger the result</em>.
	For example, when considering the
	<md> 2 t^4 - 3 t^3 </md>
	in the numerator,
	<m>t^4</m> is much, much larger than <m>t^3</m> when a large <m>t</m> is input.
	So much larger, in fact, that even though <m>3 t^3</m> is large itself,
	subtracting it from <m>2 t^4</m> does not have much of an effect on the <m>2 t^4</m>.
	And if subtracting <m>3 t^3</m> has a negligible effect,
	we may as well also ignore the extra <m>t + 4</m> in the numerator,
	which is much smaller still.
	So we can actually write
	<md> 2 t^4 - 3 t^3 + t + 4 \approx 2 t^4 </md>
	for large values of <m>t</m>.
	Similarly, in the denominator we can write
	<md> 3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6 \approx 3 t^4 </md>
	for large values of <m>t</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	In this way,
	for large values of <m>t</m> we can focus on the <term>dominant terms</term> in numerator and denominator:
	<md> f(t) \approx \frac{2 t^4}{3 t^4} = \frac{2}{3} </md>.
	The larger <m>t</m> gets,
	the more negligible the non-dominant terms become, and the more accurate the approximation above becomes,
	so we conclude that
	<md> f(t) \to \frac{2}{3} \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>.
	</p>

</example>

<warning>
	<title>Infinity is not a number</title>
	<p>
	Do <alert>not</alert> perform arithmetic with infinities.
	In particular,
	<md><mrow> \infty - \infty \amp \neq 0 \amp \frac{\infty}{\infty} \neq 1 </mrow></md>.
	</p>
</warning>

<p>
We can make the concept of <term>dominant terms</term> more precise by using
<xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-powers" />.
(Or, when appropriate, <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-of-inf" />.)
We can do this by forming ratios inside the overall ratio to more directly compare <q>large</q> terms to see who is dominant.
</p>

<heuristic xml:id="strategy-inf-behaviour-dominant-terms">
	<title>Comparing terms as <m>t \to \infty</m> in a rational expression </title>
	<statement><p>
		To determine dominant terms as <m>t \to \infty</m> in a rational expression,
		divide each term in both numerator and denominator by the
		<em>largest term in the denominator</em>.
		After simplifying and applying <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-of-inf" />,
		whatever is left are the dominant terms.
	</p></statement>
</heuristic>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-ratio-by-ratios">
	<title>Determining dominant terms</title>
	<p>
	Let's return to the function from <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-rational-infinities" />.
	We identify the <m>t^4</m> as the largest expression in the denominator,
	so we will compare every other term in the ratio to that by dividing.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(t) \amp = \frac{2 t^4 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2 t^4 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} \cdot \frac{ 1/t^4 }{ 1/t^4 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{(2 t^4 / t^4) - (3 t^3 / t^4) + (t / t^4) + (4 / t^4)}{(3 t^4 / t^4) + (4 t^3 / t^4) + (6 / t^4)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2 - (3 / t) + (1 / t^3) + (4 / t^4)}{3 + (4 / t) + (6 / t^4)} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Note that the second line above is justified by the fact that for <m>t \neq 0</m> we have
	<md> \frac{ 1/t^4 }{ 1/t^4 } = 1 </md>,
	and multiplying by <m>1</m> has no effect.
	In the last line, every term that still has a power of <m>t</m> in the denominator is eventually arbitrarily close to <m>0</m> by <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-powers" />.
	With this knowledge,
	we can say
	<md>
		<mrow> f(t) \amp = \frac{2 - (3 / t) + (1 / t^3) + (4 / t^4)}{3 + (4 / t) + (6 / t^4)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp \approx \frac{2 + 0 - 0 + 0}{3 - 0 - 0} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2}{3} </mrow>
	</md>,
	and we come to the same conclusion
	<md> f(t) \to \frac{2}{3} \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
	as in <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-rational-infinities" />.
</p>
</example>

<exercise xml:id="checkpoint-inf-behaviour-dominant-term-possibilities">
	<title>Comparing dominant terms</title>
	<p>
	Carry out a similar analysis as in <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-ratio-by-ratios" />
	for
	<md>
		<mrow>
			g(t) \amp = \frac{2 t^5 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6}
			\amp
			h(t) \amp = \frac{2 t^4 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^5 + 4 t^3 + 6}
		</mrow>
	</md>.
	How do the relative sizes of the dominant terms affect the result?
	</p>
</exercise>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Ancient behaviour</title>

<p>
The question <q>What will happen a long time from now?</q> has a flipped version:
if we have a model for how a system has behaved in recent experience,
we might want to extrapolate backwards and ask
<q>What happened a long time ago?</q>
Similar to the patterns in <xref ref="definition-inf-behaviour-horiz" />,
we write
<md> f(t) \to \pm \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to -\infty </md>
or
<md> f(t) \to L \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to -\infty </md>
when the function <m>f(t)</m> exhibits the appropriate behaviour for large but negative values of <m>t</m>.
When verifying these behaviours in examples from the definitions for <m>t \to -\infty</m>,
the process is essentially the same as that used in
<xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-parabola" /> and <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-steady-state-one-over-sq" />,
except that we now take <term>eventually</term> to mean that the behaviour
(above/below a certain proposed boundary level or within certain a proposed range around an approximate long-term value)
must hold on a subdomain <m>t \lt t_1</m> for some large, negative <m>t_1</m>.
</p>

<p>
Most of the same patterns described in <xref ref="subsection-inf-behaviour-patterns" /> still hold,
with the following alterations.
<ol>

	<li>
		The <em>plus-or-minus</em> in <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-lines" /> is flipped,
		so that a linear expression satisfies
		<md> m t + q_0 \to \mp \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to -\infty </md>,
		where the <em>minus-or-plus</em> depends on whether the constant rate factor <m>m</m> is positive or negative.
	</li>

	<li>

		<p>
		For (positive) integer exponents in <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-powers" />,
		the pattern becomes
		<md> t^m \to \pm \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to - \infty </md>,
		where the <em>plus-or-minus</em> depends on whether the exponent is even or odd.
		</p>

		<p>
		When the exponent is not an integer,
		then some care must be taken in even considering <m>t \to -\infty</m>.
		For example,
		if <m>m = 1/2</m> then there are no negative numbers in the domain of <m>f(t) = t^{1/2} = \sqrt{t}</m>,
		and so looking for a pattern in the output values for this function as <m>t \to -\infty</m> makes no sense.
		</p>

	</li>

	<li>
		Since <m>- 0 = 0</m>,
		we don't have the even/odd split in <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-reciprocal-powers" /> that we have in <xref ref="pattern-inf-behaviour-powers" />,
		but the same warning about taking care when the exponent is not an integer applies.
	</li>

</ol>
</p>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-neg-rational-infinities">
	<title>A rational expression of <q>infinities</q> for <m>t \to -\infty</m></title>

	<p>
	Let's revisit
	<md> f(t) = \frac{2 t^4 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 5} </md>
	from <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-ratio-by-ratios" />.
	The algebraic analysis in that example still holds to allow us to say
	<md> f(t) \approx \frac{2 t^4}{3 t^4} = \frac{2}{3} </md>
	for all large and <em>negative</em> values of <m>t</m>.
	This works because whether
	<md> t^m \to \infty \qquad \text{or} \qquad t^m \to -\infty </md>
	as <m>t \to -\infty</m>
	(depending on whether the exponent <m>m</m> is even or odd),
	in both cases it will be true that
	<md> \frac{1}{t^m} \to 0 \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to -\infty </md>.
	So we can still use <term>dominant terms</term> to analyze the ancient behaviour of a rational function like this,
	and in this case we see that the ancient behaviour and the long-term behaviour are identical.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-two-sided-horiz-asymp">
		<caption> A function with a symmetric horizontal asymptote. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-two-sided-horiz-asymp" width="99.7%">
			<shortdescription> The graph of a function with a symmetric horizontal asymptote. </shortdescription>
			<description><p>
				The graph of a function is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes,
				and the horizontal line <m>q = 2/3</m> is also drawn as a dashed line as a horizontal asymptote for the function at both the extreme left- and right-end of the graph.
				The graph begins at the far left of the view near but slightly above its horizontal asymptote,
				then slowly rises.
				As it nears the vertical axis,
				it begins to rise steeply until it reaches a peak,
				then drops sharply before flattening out near the horizontal asymptote line.
				Over this short flat stretch it crosses the vertical axis just above the horizontal asymptote before crossing the that asymptote as it descends to a trough just above the horizontal axis.
				From there,
				it slowly rises again,
				approaching the horizontal axis from below as it nears the right edge of the view.
			</p></description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/two-sided-horiz-asymp.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<warning>
	<title>Ancient and long-term behaviour can be different</title>
	<p>
	We should not take from <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-neg-rational-infinities" /> that the behaviour as <m>t \to -\infty</m> will always be the same as the behaviour as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	</p>
</warning>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-non-symmetric-hasymps">
	<title>Different analyses may be required for <m>t \to \pm \infty</m></title>

	<p>
	For function <md> f(t) = \frac{\sqrt{2 t^2 + 1}}{3 t - 5} </md>,
	first consider <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	Analyzing dominant terms,
	we may consider both the <q>plus one</q> in the numerator and the <q>minus five</q> in the denominator as negligible for large values of <m>t</m>,
	so that
	<md>
		<mrow> f(t) \amp \approx \frac{\sqrt{2 t^2}}{3 t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{t \sqrt{2}}{3 t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} </mrow>
	</md>.
	So we conclude that <md> f(t) \to \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>.
	</p>

	<p>
	For <m>t \to -\infty</m> our analysis of dominant terms above remains the same,
	but there is one algebraic manipulation that is only valid for positive values of <m>t</m>.
	The simplification <md> \sqrt{2 t^2} = t \sqrt{2} </md> is <em>not</em> valid for negative values of <m>t</m>,
	which is what we are considering when we analyze <m>t \to -\infty</m>.
	For example, for <m>t = -1</m> we have
	<md>
		<mrow> \sqrt{2 t^2} \amp = \sqrt{2 {(-1)}^2} \amp t \sqrt{2} \amp = (-1) \sqrt{2} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sqrt{2} \amp \amp = -\sqrt{2} </mrow>
	</md>
	and the two expressions are not equal.
	Ignoring the <m>2</m> for the moment,
	the correct simplification in all cases is <md> \sqrt{t^2} = \abs{t} </md>,
	it's just that when <m>t</m> is positive we can ignore the absolute value brackets.
	</p>

	<p>
	Reworking our algebraic manipulations then,
	for large and <em>negative</em> values of <m>t</m> we have
	<md>
		<mrow> f(t) \amp \approx \frac{\sqrt{2 t^2}}{3 t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{2} \abs{t}}{3 t} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Now, <md> \frac{\abs{t}}{t} = - 1 </md>,
	when <m>t</m> is negative since the numerator and denominator have the same magnitude but one is positive and the other is negative.
	So we have <md> f(t) \approx - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}</md> for large, negative values of <m>t</m>
	and we conclude that <md> f(t) \to - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to -\infty </md>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-separate-two-sided-horiz-asymp">
		<caption> A graph with two different horizontal asymptotes. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-separate-two-sided-horiz-asymp" width="92%">
			<shortdescription> The graph of a function with two different horizontal asymptotes. </shortdescription>
			<description><p>
				The graph of a function with two horizontal asymptotes,
				one each at <m>q = \pm \sqrt{2} / 3</m> (drawn with dashed lines)
				is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
				The graph begins just above the horizontal asymptote at <m>q = - \sqrt{2} / 3</m> at the left edge of the view,
				rising slowing towards its vertical intercept just below the horizontal axis.
				It reaches a peak near this intercept,
				and then descends sharply as it approaches a vertical asymptote at <m>t = 5/3</m> from the left.
				On the right side of this vertical asymptote,
				the graph descends steeply from the top edge of the view and but quickly flattens out as it slowly approaches the horizontal asymptote at <m>q = \sqrt{2} / 3</m> from above.
			</p></description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/separate-two-sided-horiz-asymp.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Slant asymptotes</title>

<p> Sometimes we can be more informative about the patterns <m>f(t) \to \pm \infty</m>. </p>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-eventually-linear">
	<title>An <q>eventually linear</q> function</title>
	<p>
	In your analysis of
	<md> g(t) = \frac{2 t^5 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </md>
	in <xref ref="checkpoint-inf-behaviour-dominant-term-possibilities" />,
	you should have found that
	<md> g(t) \approx \frac{2 t}{3} </md>
	for large values of <m>t</m>,
	whether positive or negative.
	From this we can conclude that
	<md> g(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
	and
	<md> g(t) \to -\infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to -\infty </md>.
	However, the expression
	<md> g(t) \approx \frac{2}{3} t </md>
	is actually more informative about exactly <em>how</em> <m>g(t) \to \pm \infty</m>;
	in particular, it says that <m>g(t)</m> is essentially linear for large values of <m>t</m>,
	growing at approximately constant rate <m>2/3</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	However, there may be an <q>offset</q> to how it grows linearly.
	To see this,
	let's investigate more closely how the numerator and denominator polynomials relate.
	In the numerator, the only term that matters is the <m>2 t^5</m> since the other terms are <q>small</q> compared to the <m>3 t^4</m> in the denominator:
	<md>
		<mrow> g(t) \amp = \frac{2 t^5 - 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2 t^5}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} + \frac{- 3 t^3 + t + 4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp \approx \frac{2 t^5}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
	</md>,
	where the <em>approximately equal</em> is true for large <m>t</m>.
	Now let's make the numerator look more like the denominator.
	<md>
		<mrow> g(t) \amp \approx \frac{2 t^5}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2 t \cdot \frac{t^4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2}{3} \, t \cdot \frac{3 t^4}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2}{3} \, t \cdot \frac{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6 - (4 t^3 + 6)}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
	</md>.
	In this last step, we have added and then immediately subtracted some terms to make the numerator look even more like the denominator,
	while maintaining equality with the previous expression.
	Continuing,
	<md>
		<mrow> g(t) \amp \approx \frac{2}{3} \, t \cdot \frac{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6 - (4 t^3 + 6)}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6} </mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp =
			\frac{2}{3} \, t \cdot \frac{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6}
			- \frac{2}{3} \, t \cdot \frac{4 t^3 + 6}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp =
			\frac{2}{3} \, t \cdot 1
			- \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{4 t^4 + 6 t}{3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6}
		</mrow>
	</md>.
	Looking at the dominant terms in the remaining rational expression,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow>
			g(t) \amp \approx
			\frac{2}{3} \, t
			- \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{4}{3}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{2}{3} \, t - \frac{8}{9} </mrow>
	</md>.
	We conclude that for large <m>t</m>,
	the graph of <m>g(t)</m> will look like the line
	<md> y = \frac{2}{3} \, t - \frac{8}{9} </md>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-slant-asymp">
		<caption>
			A graph with a slant asymptote.
			The graph will slowly approach the dashed line both to the upper right and the lower left.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-slant-asymp" width="100%">
			<shortdescription> The graph of a function with a slant asymptote. </shortdescription>
			<description><p>
				The graph of a function with a slant asymptote is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
				The slant axis <m>q = (2 / 3) t - 8 / 9</m> is drawn as a dashed line.
				This line has a positive slope and runs from the bottom-left corner to the top-right corner of the view,
				crossing the vertical axis at <m>q = - 8 / 9</m> and then crossing the horizontal axis at <m>t = 4 / 3</m>.
				The graph of the function begins in the bottom-left corner of the view,
				very close but slightly above the asymptote line.
				It continues to follow that line very closely,
				but in the approximate middle of the portion of the third quadrant that is in view,
				the graph crosses the asymptote and rises much more steeply,
				crossing the negative horizontal axis as well before coming to a peak in the second quadrant.
				The graph then descends a short distance before flattening out as it crosses positive vertical axis.
				The graph then dips to a trough in the first quadrant just above the asymptote line's horizontal intercept,
				before rising to follow the asymptote line very closely from above to the top-right corner of the view.
			</p></description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/slant-asymp.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-slant-asymp">
	<title>Slant asymptote</title>
	<statement><p>
		A line with non-zero slope that a function's graph approaches,
		becoming closer and closer to it as one goes further out on the graph.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

</subsection>

<!-- TODO Sage ? -->

</section>

<section xml:id="section-inf-behaviour-relative-growth">
<title>Comparing growth of two functions</title>

<p>
There are two simple algebraic ways we can compare two expressions <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>:
using a difference <m>A - B</m> or using a ratio <m>A / B</m>.
However, the result of a difference is dependent on both magnitude and the combination of signs of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
whereas a ratio tends to keep the matters of signs and relative magnitudes separate.
Furthermore,
we can more easily perform algebraic manipulations in a ratio without changing the actual value of it.
</p>

<p>
In the case of two functions <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> which both satisfy
<md><mrow> f(t) \amp \to \infty \amp g(t) \amp \to \infty </mrow></md>
as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
we can compare how fast each grows to <m>\infty</m> by forming a ratio of their output values and re-analyzing as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
Effectively,
this pits them against each other in a race to <m>\infty</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-relative-rates">
	<title>Relative rates of growth</title>
	<statement><p>
		Assume functions <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> both satisfy
		<md><mrow> f(t) \amp \to \infty \amp g(t) \amp \to \infty </mrow></md>
		as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
		<ol>

			<li>
				<title>Faster growth</title>
				<p>
				If <md> \frac{f(t)}{g(t)} \to \infty \text{ as } t \to \infty </md>
				then we say that <m>f(t)</m> <term>grows faster than</term> <m>g(t)</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Slower growth</title>
				<p>
				If <md> \frac{f(t)}{g(t)} \to 0 \text{ as } t \to \infty </md>
				then we say that <m>f(t)</m> <term>grows more slowly than</term> <m>g(t)</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Comparable growth</title>
				<p>
				If <md> \frac{f(t)}{g(t)} \to L \text{ as } t \to \infty </md>
				where <m>L</m> is a positive, finite number,
				then we say that <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> <term>grow at comparable rates</term>.
				</p>
			</li>

		</ol>
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<remark><p>
	In the third case in <xref ref="definition-inf-behaviour-relative-rates" />,
	it is not necessary for <m>L</m> to be <m>1</m> to be able to say that <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> grow at comparable rates <mdash />
	any other value for <m>L</m> represents an approximate scale factor between <m>g(t)</m> and <m>f(t)</m> as they grow in tandem.
</p></remark>

<p>
We will revisit this concept of <term>relative rate of growth</term> several times in later chapters as we grow our stable of important functions.
For now,
here are some simple examples based on computations we have already performed.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Growing at a faster rate</title>
	<p>
	We can re-interpret the calculations of <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-eventually-linear" />
	by setting
	<md><mrow>
		f(t) \amp = 2 t^5 - 3 t^3 + t + 4
		\amp
		g(t) = 3 t^4 + 4 t^3 + 6
	</mrow></md>.
	These two function satisfy
	<md><mrow> f(t) \amp \to \infty \amp g(t) \amp \to \infty </mrow></md>
	as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	In that previous example,
	we analyzed the long-term behaviour of the ratio of these two functions and found that
	<md> \frac{f(t)}{g(t)} \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>,
	which tells us that <m>f(t)</m> grows faster than <m>g(t)</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Growing at a comparable rate</title>
	<p>
	We can re-interpret the calculations of <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-non-symmetric-hasymps" />
	by setting
	<md><mrow>
		f(t) \amp = \sqrt{2 t^2 + 1}
		\amp
		g(t) = 3 t - 5
	</mrow></md>.
	These two function satisfy
	<md><mrow> f(t) \amp \to \infty \amp g(t) \amp \to \infty </mrow></md>
	as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	In that previous example,
	we analyzed the long-term behaviour of the ratio of these two functions and found that
	<md> \frac{f(t)}{g(t)} \to \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>,
	which tells us that <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> grow at comparable rates,
	though eventually <md> f(t) \approx \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} \, g(t) </md>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>


<section>
<title>Singular behaviour</title>

<subsection>
<title>Concept, definition, and basic examples</title>

<p>
With a mathematical for a system in hand,
another natural question to ask is
<q>Are there any input values near which the output values become unbounded?</q>
(For example,
if you have a mathematical model of an energy supply,
you might want to know if there are any particular operating states that cause it to create an enormous surge of energy.)
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-singular">
	<title>Singular behaviour</title>
	<statement><p>
		<ol>

			<li>
				<title>Growth singularity</title>
				<p>
					We write <md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to c </md>
					to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> become arbitrarily large and positive for all inputs <m>t</m> sufficiently close to (but not equal to) <m>c</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Decay singularity</title>
				<p>
					We write <md> f(t) \to -\infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to c </md>
					to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> become arbitrarily large and negative for all inputs <m>t</m> sufficiently close to (but not equal to) <m>c</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

		</ol>
		In either case,
		we say that <m>f(t)</m> has a <term>singularity</term> at <m>t = c</m>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<p>
In <xref ref="definition-inf-behaviour-singular" />,
<term>arbitrarily large</term> means just the same as it did when we defined long-term behaviour.
And <term>sufficiently close</term> means essentially the same as <term>arbitrarily close</term>,
except
<ol>

	<li>
		the change from <term>arbitrarily</term> to <term>sufficiently</term> reflects the fact that we are in control of how close to <m>c</m> we need to restrict <m>t</m> to be in order to achieve the arbitrarily large outputs
	</li>

	<li> we don't necessarily require a symmetric subdomain around <m>t = c</m>. </li>

</ol>
</p>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-1-over-square-singularity">
	<title>The prototypical growth singularity</title>
	<p>
	Consider values of the function <md>f(t) = \frac{1}{t^2}</md> near <m>t = 0</m>.
	We can't actually evaluate <m>f(0)</m> because that involves division by zero.
	But if <m>t \approx 0</m> then <m>f(t)</m> is very large and positive.
	<ul>

		<li>
			Do values of <m>f(t)</m> grow at least as large as <m>100</m> for <m>t \approx 0</m>?
			Yes, they will do so for all <m>t</m> in the subdomain <m>0 \pm 0.1</m> (excluding <m>t = 0</m>).
		</li>

		<li>
			Do values of <m>f(t)</m> grow at least as large as <m>100</m> trillion for <m>t \approx 0</m>?
			Yes, they will do so for all <m>t</m> in the subdomain <m>0 \pm {10}^{-7}</m> (excluding <m>t = 0</m>).
		</li>

	</ul>
	In fact,
	you can answer the above question for every proposed upper limit value <m>M</m>
	by restricting <m>t</m> to be within the subdomain <md>0 \pm \frac{1}{\sqrt{M}} </md>
	(excluding <m>t = 0</m>, as always).
	From this we conclude
	<md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to 0 </md>,
	and so <m>f(t)</m> has a singularity at <m>t = 0</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<warning>
	<title>Infinity is not a number</title>
	<p>
	As we've already warned before,
	you should not attempt to perform arithmetic with <m>\infty</m>.
	</p>
</warning>

<example><p>
	Consider <md> f(t) = \frac{1}{t^4} - \frac{1}{t^2} </md>.
	In <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-1-over-square-singularity" />,
	we have already demonstrated that <md> \frac{1}{t^2} \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to 0 </md>.
	A similar analysis would show that <md> \frac{1}{t^4} \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to 0 </md>.
	So it would seem that in the difference in the formula for <m>f(t)</m>,
	the two infinities would cancel, and we should have <m>f(t) \approx 0</m> for <m>t \approx 0</m>.
	But this is not the case,
	since if we use a common denominator we have
	<md>
		<mrow> f(t) \amp = \frac{1}{t^4} - \frac{1}{t^2} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1 - t^2}{t^4} </mrow>
	</md>.
	For <m>t \approx 0</m>, the numerator of this new formula for <m>f(t)</m> is approximately <m>1</m>,
	but the denominator is very small and positive,
	so the ratio is very large.
	That is, <m>f(t)</m> has a singularity at <m>t = 0</m> with
	<md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to 0 </md>.
	Looking back at the original difference formula for <m>f(t)</m>,
	we can interpret this as saying that for <m>t \approx 0</m>,
	the size of <m>1/t^4</m> is so large as to make the subtraction of <m>1/t^2</m> negligible.
</p></example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>One-sided singularities</title>

<p>
For some functions,
it is the case that the values become large and positive on one side of a singularity and large and negative on the other side.
To handle this sort of situation,
we make the following definition.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-one-sided-singular">
	<title>One-sided singular behaviour</title>
	<statement><p>
		<ol>

			<li>
				<title>Right-hand singularity</title>
				<p>
					We write <md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to c^+ </md>
					to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> become arbitrarily large and positive for all inputs <m>t</m> sufficiently close to but strictly greater than <m>c</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Left-hand singularity</title>
				<p>
					We write <md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to c^- </md>
					to mean that output values of <m>f(t)</m> become arbitrarily large and positive for all inputs <m>t</m> sufficiently close to but strictly less than <m>c</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

		</ol>
		And we can make similar definitions for the meanings of <m>f(t) \to -\infty</m> as <m>t \to c^+</m> or as <m>t \to c^-</m>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="example-inf-behaviour-two-sided-singularity">
	<title>A function with different one-sided singular behaviours</title>
	<p>
	Consider function <md> f(t) = \frac{t - 2}{t - 1} </md>.
	For <m>t \approx 1</m> but greater than <m>1</m>,
	the numerator is approximately <m>-1</m> but the denominator is small and positive,
	making the ratio very large and negative.
	Hence <md> f(t) \to -\infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to 1^+ </md>.
	For <m>t \approx 1</m> but less than <m>1</m>,
	the numerator is still approximately <m>-1</m> but the denominator is now small and negative,
	making the ratio very large and positive.
	Hence <md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to 1^- </md>.
	</p>
</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Vertical asymptotes</title>

<p>
Recall that,
graphically,
long-term behaviour
<md> f(t) \to \mathrm{constant} \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \infty </md>
means the function's graph is approaching a <xref ref="definition-inf-behaviour-hasymp" text="title" />
at the height of the constant that the output levels are approaching.
For singular behaviour
<md> f(t) \to \infty \qquad \text{as} \qquad t \to \mathrm{constant} </md>
this is reversed,
so that the function's graph is approaching a <em>vertical</em> line at a specific value of <m>t</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-inf-behaviour-vasymp">
	<title>Vertical asymptote</title>
	<statement><p>
		A vertical line that a function's graph approaches,
		becoming closer and closer to it as the inputs are made closer to the location of the vertical line.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-vert-asymp">
	<caption> Two kinds of vertical asymptotes. </caption>

	<sidebyside widths="34.7% 34.7%">

		<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-vert-asymp-1">
			<caption>
				A function that displays the same behaviour on either side of a vertical asymptote.
				(From <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-1-over-square-singularity" />.)
			</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-vert-asymp-1">
				<shortdescription> The graph of a function that displays the same behaviour on either side of a vertical asymptote. </shortdescription>
				<description><p>
					The graph of a function with a vertical asymptote at <m>t = 0</m> is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
					On both the left and right sides of the asymptote line,
					the graph is unbounded in the positive direction,
					so that the graph appears to <q>rise to infinity</q> on both sides.
				</p></description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/vert-asymp-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure xml:id="figure-inf-behaviour-vert-asymp-2">
			<caption>
				A function that displays different behaviours on either side of a vertical asymptote.
				(From <xref ref="example-inf-behaviour-two-sided-singularity" />.)
			</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-inf-behaviour-vert-asymp-2">
				<shortdescription> The graph of a function that displays different behaviours on either side of a vertical asymptote. </shortdescription>
				<description><p>
					The graph of a function with a vertical asymptote at an unspecified position on the positive horizontal axis is drawn on a set of <m>tq</m>-axes.
					This asymptote is drawn as a dashed vertical line.
					On the left of the asymptote,
					the graph is unbounded in the positive direction,
					so that the graph appears to <q>rise to infinity</q> on this side.
					But on the right of the asymptote,
					the graph is unbounded in the negative direction,
					so that the graph appears to <q>descend to negative infinity</q> on this side.
				</p></description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="inf-behaviour.d/vert-asymp-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

</subsection>

</section>


